<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>The point is that the 1% can potentially turn into a huge amount of money. Let's take the most extreme example: Facebook. If they gave 1% of their equity to a cause in the early stages, it doesn't seem like much. But with their IPO, it's now worth $1 billion. Facebook would never give a $1B donation to charity now, but they are held accountable to what they originally gave in equity.</font></span><p><font size=1><u><a href="reply?id=3831365&whence=%69%74%65%6d%3f%69%64%3d%33%38%33%31%32%31%34">reply</a></u></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=80></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_3831674 href="vote?for=3831674&dir=up&whence=%69%74%65%6d%3f%69%64%3d%33%38%33%31%32%31%34"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_3831674></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=alastair">alastair</a> 1 hour ago  | <a href="item?id=3831674">link</a></span></div><br>
